[[File:Arbelas-knife.gif|thumb|alt=Drawing of curved knife with T-handle|Arbelos]] The '''''arbelas''''' (plural ''arbelai'') was a [[List of Roman gladiator types|type]] of [[ancient Roman]] [[gladiator]]. The word is a ''[[hapax legomenon]]'', occurring only in the ''[[Oneirocritica]]'' of [[Artemidorus]], a Greek work on [[dream interpretation]] that discusses the symbolism of various [[List of Roman gladiator types|gladiator types]].<ref name=Duncan>{{cite book|first=Anne|last=Duncan|title=Performance and Identity in the Classical World|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2006|page=205}}</ref> It may be related to the Greek word ''arbelos'' (ἄρβηλος), a [[Shoemaking|cobbler]]'s semicircular blade used to cut leather<ref name=Duncan /><ref name=Fagan>{{cite book|first=Garret G.|last=Fagan|title=The Lure of the Arena: Social Psychology and the Crowd at the Roman Games|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|page=217}}</ref><ref name=Carter>{{cite journal|first=Michael|last=Carter|title=Artemidorus and the Arbelas Gladiator|journal=Zeitschrift für Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=134|year=2001|pages=109–115|jstor=20190801}} {{subscription required|date=January 2012}}</ref> similar to an [[ulu]].
A few [[relief]]s show gladiators armed with a curved blade fighting each other; it has been argued that these (possibly also fighting ''[[retiarius|retiarii]]'', the net-fighters) are ''arbelai'';<ref name=Carter /> however, they have also been seen as the ''[[Scissor (gladiator type)|scissores]]'' who likewise may have been matched against ''retiarii''.<ref name=Fagan /><ref name=Carter2>{{cite journal|first=Michael|last=Carter|title=Gladiatorial Combat with 'Sharp' Weapons (τοι̑ϛ ὀξέσι σιδήροιϛ)|journal=Zeitschrift für Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=155|year=2006|pages=161–175|jstor=20191036}} {{subscription required|date=January 2012}}</ref> The ''scissor'', with whom the ''arbelas'' may be synonymous, is referred to in a roll call from the gladiator training school ''([[Ludus (ancient Rome)|ludus]])'' owned in the 1st century BC by the ''[[lanista]]'' C. Salvius Capito.{{citation needed|date=January 2012}}
Artemidorus lists the ''arbelas'' among gladiators who might appear in dreams advising a man about what sort of woman he is to marry. Both the ''[[dimachaerus]]'', who fought with two curved blades, and the "so-called" ''arbelas'' signify that the woman will either be a [[Venefica sorceress|poisoner]], malicious, or ugly.<ref name=Carter /><ref>{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Carter|editor1-first=J. C.|editor1-last=Edmondson|editor2-first=Alison|editor2-last=Keith|chapter=(Un)Dressed to Kill: Viewing the ''Retiarius''|title=Roman Dress and the Fabrics of Roman Culture|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2008|page=129}}</ref>
