The '''Center for Appropriate Transport''' (CAT) is a [[Non-profit organization|non-profit]] [[Community centre|community center]] dedicated to [[bicycle]]s and [[Sustainable transport|alternative transport]] located in [[Eugene, Oregon]], United States.<ref name=Cargo>{{cite journal |url= http://www.bicycling.com/bikes-and-gear-features/reviews/coolest-bike-ever-made |title= Why Cargo Bikes Are Cycling's Coolest Inventions |first=Tom |last= Clynes |date= September 7, 2011 |journal= [[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]] |accessdate= January 2, 2016}}</ref>
CAT holds publicly funded educational workshops for teaching youth from ages 12 to 21. Within the {{convert|8000|sqft|m2|sing=on}} facility there is a public bicycle repair workspace and a bike machine-shop for the design and manufacture of special-purpose bikes, particularly cargo bikes and [[Recumbent bicycle|recumbents]]. There is also a bike museum on site, a bike rack-building workshop, and a sewing facility. CAT formerly held the offices of ''Oregon Cycling'' magazine, which ceased publishing in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bikeportland.org/2009/08/07/oregon-cycling-magazine-shuts-down-new-owners-look-to-bring-it-back-22060 |publisher= Bike Portland |title= Oregon Cycling Magazine Shuts Down; New Owners Look to Bring it Back |first= Jonathan |last= Maus |date= August 7, 2009}}</ref> CAT is also home to Pedaler's Express, a pioneering [[workbike]]-based delivery service.<ref name=Yoshiyuki>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_nrD0LlcIUEC&lpg=PA78&ots=f1FqPfGU5H&dq=%22center+for+appropriate+transport%22&pg=PA78 |last= Nagata |first= Yoshiyuki |title= Center for Appropriate Transport |work=Alternative Education: Global Perspectives Relevant to the Asia-Pacific Region |year= 2006 |publisher=Springer Verlag |page= 78 |isbn= 978-1-4020-4985-9}}</ref>
== History == CAT was founded in 1992.<ref name=Yoshiyuki/>
To create the center, [[Jan VanderTuin]] gathered the founding core group, which included bicycle retailer and activist Kurt Jensen, writer and racer Jason Moore, Bowerman, and ''Rain Magazine'' editors [[Greg Bryant (computer scientist)|Greg Bryant]] and Danielle Janes. Bryant was instrumental in bringing ''Oregon Cycling'' into CAT, and obtaining non-profit status. CAT opened on November 20, 1992.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.rainmagazine.com/archive/1993/cat01292014 |title= CAT |journal= Rain |first= Jason |last= Moore |year= 1993 |accessdate= January 2, 2016}}</ref>
Within a few years CAT and ''Rain Magazine'' were no longer partners, and by 1995 the emphasis turned to youth education when CAT began contracting with local school districts to work with youth in need of a hands-on education. CAT is an [[alternative education]] program registered with the [[Oregon Department of Education]] and as such is one of the few publicly funded bicycle schools in the United States.
